                [
                          "[[image:toolkit-quick-poll/01.png|Quick Poll default launch screen]]\n\nClick the **Quick Poll** icon in the toolbar at the bottom of the class screen to open the instant poll window. Quick Poll is used to ask a short question during class and immediately count student responses.\n\nIn the top tabs, select the format you want to use from **Agree/Disagree**, **Traffic Light**, **Opinion Scale**, and **Vote**. Enter the question in the **Enter Directly** area at the top.",
                          "Quick Poll adjusts the response count with the **− / +** buttons next to each option. It is suitable when the teacher needs to immediately record, on the class screen, results from students raising hands or answering verbally.\n\nIf you count a response incorrectly, use the **−** button to reduce the count; if there are additional responses, use the **+** button to increase it. By changing the format, you can quickly check the same question with a different response method.",
                          "Quick Poll provides four available formats.\n\n- **Agree/Disagree** : Quickly check opinions with two options, such as agree/disagree.\n\n- **Traffic Light** : Divide responses into three levels: Agree, Neutral, and Disagree.\n\n- **Opinion Scale** : Check the strength of opinions on a 5-point scale.\n\n- **Vote** : Let students choose from options entered directly by the teacher.",
                          "[[image:toolkit-quick-poll/06.png|Agree Disagree response count screen]]\n\n**Agree/Disagree** is used for questions that are clearly divided, such as agreement and disagreement. After entering the question, adjust the count for **Agree** or **Disagree** according to student responses.\n\nUse it to quickly check the distribution of opinions before a discussion or when asking a short agree/disagree question during class.",
                          "[[image:toolkit-quick-poll/07.png|Traffic Light question entry screen]]\n\n**Traffic Light** is used when you want to check student responses in three levels. It is displayed as green **Agree**, yellow **Neutral**, and red **Disagree**, so students can intuitively understand what each response means.\n\nIt is suitable for questions where opinions are not completely split, or for situations that need a middle response, such as understanding, confidence, or preference.",
                          "[[image:toolkit-quick-poll/12.png|Opinion Scale response count screen]]\n\n**Opinion Scale** counts the strength of opinions on a 5-point scale. Use it when you want to see how strongly students agree or disagree, rather than simply separating agree/disagree.\n\nIt is suitable for questions where the degree of response matters, such as a post-class survey, checking positions on a discussion topic, or checking satisfaction with an activity.",
                          "[[image:toolkit-quick-poll/13.png|Vote option entry screen]]\n\n**Vote** is a format where the teacher directly enters options to create a poll. Write the options in the option input fields, and add options with the **+** button if needed.\n\nUse it when students should choose one from fixed options, such as selecting a class topic, deciding an activity method, or gathering student opinions. Delete unused options and leave only the options that will actually be used for voting to make the screen clearer."
                ]
