      "body": [
        "**Brainstorming** is an Idea Board Activity where the teacher asks one question and students freely write and collect their own opinions.\n\nInstead of marking answers as correct or incorrect, it collects diverse ideas in one place and organizes the submitted opinions as **Word Cloud / Classification / Mind Map** so they can be reviewed at a glance.",
        "[[image:idea-board-brainstorming/01.png|Select Brainstorming in the Create Manually window]]\n\nWhen adding a slide on the class editing screen, select **Idea Board** from the left menu in the **Create Manually** window. The **Idea Board** category includes **Brainstorming**, **Whiteboard**, and **Ideas** activities. Click **Brainstorming** to add the slide.\n\n- **Brainstorming**: An activity for freely collecting opinions about a question.\n- **Whiteboard**: An activity for freely drawing and writing.\n- **Ideas**: An activity for organizing ideas.\n\n[[image:idea-board-brainstorming/02.png|Brainstorming question input area]]\n\nClick the **Enter Question** area in the center of the slide and enter the question you want to ask students. When you select text, the formatting toolbar appears, where you can set the font, font size, alignment, **B / I / U**, text color, and delete option.\n\nExample question: **What can we do to protect the Earth?**\n\n[[image:idea-board-brainstorming/03.png|Brainstorming question and right settings panel]]\n\nIn the right panel, configure how the activity works.\n\n- **Background Color**: Select the slide background color.\n- **Classify Opinion Result**: When turned on, AI automatically organizes the collected opinions.\n- **Word Cloud**: Shows frequently used words larger in a word cloud.\n- **Classification**: Classifies opinions by topic category.\n- **Mind Map**: Connects opinions as branches around the question.\n- **Response Visibility**: Choose whether student opinions are visible to **Teacher Only** or **Teacher & Students**.\n- **Response Limit**: Choose how many times each student can submit, either **One Time** or **Unlimited**.\n- **Nickname Shown**: When turned on, the author nickname is shown with the opinion.\n- **Time Limit**: When turned on, you can set a time limit for the activity.\n\n> ⚠️ **Classify Opinion Result** uses AI, so credits are deducted.",
        "[[image:idea-board-brainstorming/04.png|Brainstorming class start screen]]\n\nWhen the class starts, the **Access Code** students can use to join and the question are shown on the screen. The upper right shows **Instructor View** and **End Lesson**, and the lower right shows the number of students currently connected. When ready, click **Let's Begin** to start collecting opinions.\n\n[[image:idea-board-brainstorming/05.png|Student opinion cards in Post-it view]]\n\nAfter the activity begins, students submit their opinions. In **Post-it** view, submitted opinions appear as note cards. Students who have not submitted yet appear as question mark cards, and once submission is complete, the card is filled with the author's name and opinion.\n\n[[image:idea-board-brainstorming/06.png|Live Wordcloud view]]\n\nIn **Live Wordcloud** view, the words students enter are reflected in the word cloud in real time. More frequent words are shown larger. Use the **Show Response** toggle at the lower left to control whether student opinions are shown.\n\n[[image:idea-board-brainstorming/07.png|Result form selection window]]\n\nTo finish collecting responses, click **Finish Up** at the lower right. Then use **View Result** to check the collected opinions in an organized view. If you click the format button next to **View Result**, the **Result form** window opens. Select the desired format and click **Change** to switch.\n\n[[image:idea-board-brainstorming/08.png|Classification result screen]]\n\n**Classification** automatically classifies opinions by topic category. While classification is in progress, the **Generating BrainStorming Results..** message is shown. When complete, the number of opinions in each category appears. Click a category to view the related opinion cards together with author names.\n\n[[image:idea-board-brainstorming/09.png|Mind Map result screen]]\n\n**Mind Map** places the question as the central node and connects topics and details as branches. Use **+ / -** on each node to expand or collapse branches, and use the **- / + / 100%** controls at the lower left to zoom and move the view.",
        "[[image:idea-board-brainstorming/10.png|Brainstorming waiting state on the student screen]]\n\nUntil the teacher starts the activity, the student screen shows **Please wait until your teacher starts the activity.**\n\n[[image:idea-board-brainstorming/11.png|Student opinion input and Submit button]]\n\nWhen the teacher starts the activity, the question is displayed, and students write their opinion in the **Write your opinion** input field at the bottom. After entering an opinion, click **Submit** to submit it.\n\nWhen the input field is empty, the **Submit** button is disabled. Once text is entered, it turns blue and becomes active. If **Response Limit** is set to **Unlimited**, students can submit multiple times; if it is set to **One Time**, they can submit only once."
      ]
